03:29.944 --> 03:31.777
<i> ¶ My paddle's keen and bright</i>

03:31.779 --> 03:33.712
<i> ¶ Flashing with silver</i>

03:33.714 --> 03:35.214
<i> ¶ Follow the wild</i>
<i> goose flight</i>

03:35.216 --> 03:37.282
<i> ¶ Dip, dip and swing ¶</i>

03:37.284 --> 03:39.051
<i> ¶ Dip, dip and</i>
<i> swing her back ¶</i>

03:39.053 --> 03:41.053
<i> ¶ Flashing with silver</i>

03:41.055 --> 03:43.288
<i> ¶ Follow the wild goose flight</i>

03:43.290 --> 03:45.290
<i> ¶ Dip, dip and swing ¶</i>

03:45.292 --> 03:52.531
(boys laughing)

03:52.533 --> 03:54.166
Joseph:
<i> Guys, guys.</i>

03:54.168 --> 03:56.268
<i>Do you wanna see a magic trick?</i>
Will:<i> I do. Let me see it.</i>

03:56.270 --> 03:57.603
(sneezes)
Bless you.

03:57.605 --> 03:59.938
Vernon:
<i> Ooh, what do we got here?</i>
<i> Frank:No, no, no, no, no.</i>

03:59.940 --> 04:01.807
Frank:
<i> Hey, let, hey, let go!</i>

04:01.809 --> 04:03.308
(laughs)

04:06.013 --> 04:07.346
That's a keen wristwatch.

04:08.549 --> 04:09.881
Ingersole Radiolite.

04:09.883 --> 04:11.550
Tells the time in the dark.

04:11.552 --> 04:14.186
<i> You never know how much you</i>
<i> need one 'til you own one.</i>

04:14.188 --> 04:15.287
Will:
<i> I want one.</i>

04:15.289 --> 04:17.055
I'll leave it to you
in my will, kiddo.

04:17.057 --> 04:18.323
Thanks.

04:22.997 --> 04:23.996
Jack?

04:23.998 --> 04:25.297
Yeah, Willis?

04:27.268 --> 04:28.533
Jesus, Will.

04:31.805 --> 04:33.105
Thanks.

04:33.107 --> 04:35.173
It's gonna be a swell
trip with him in tow.

04:35.809 --> 04:37.709
I'm gonna kill him.

04:39.146 --> 04:45.150
(gentle instrumental)

04:45.152 --> 04:48.220
¶

05:00.234 --> 05:03.368
(boys chattering)

05:21.488 --> 05:23.155
Hello, pleasure to meet you.

05:23.157 --> 05:24.723
My second-in-command.

05:24.725 --> 05:25.991
<i> Arthur Lambden.</i>

05:26.860 --> 05:28.126
Robert Butcher.

05:30.130 --> 05:31.463
This is the
Brotherhood of St. Andrew.

05:31.465 --> 05:33.131
Hello, boys.

05:33.133 --> 05:34.800
Hello, sir.
-Hello to you, sir.

05:34.802 --> 05:36.134
You may fall in line
next to Leonard.

05:36.136 --> 05:37.436
Very good.

05:40.374 --> 05:41.640
(whistle blows)

05:43.444 --> 05:46.545
Robert:
<i> We've operated a boys'</i>
<i> camp for years at Clear Lake.</i>

05:46.547 --> 05:48.313
This is our first
time at Long Point.

05:48.315 --> 05:49.614
(sneezes)

05:50.217 --> 05:51.483
Sorry, sir.

05:51.485 --> 05:53.185
I'm Leonard O'Hara.

05:54.955 --> 05:56.388
I have hypersensitivities.

05:56.390 --> 05:57.656
To what?

05:58.158 --> 05:59.157
Trees.

05:59.159 --> 06:01.226
(laughter)

06:03.664 --> 06:12.871
(gentle instrumental)
(boys laughing and chatting)

06:12.873 --> 06:14.172
Will:
<i> We're here.</i>

06:15.609 --> 06:18.610
(boys laughing)

06:18.612 --> 06:19.878
(whistle blows)

06:20.447 --> 06:21.713
Robert:
<i> Parade rest!</i>

06:23.951 --> 06:25.150
Let's get to work, boys.

06:25.152 --> 06:26.151
Whoo!

06:26.153 --> 06:27.152
(upbeat jazz music)

06:27.154 --> 06:28.453
Yeah!

06:28.455 --> 06:34.493
(upbeat jazz music)

06:34.495 --> 06:36.862
¶

06:36.864 --> 06:38.864
Hi, Will.
-Hi, Gordon.

06:38.866 --> 06:40.332
Will, thanks.

06:42.069 --> 06:43.068
Vern, go field.

06:43.070 --> 06:44.169
Vernon:
<i> Over into it.</i>

06:44.171 --> 06:45.437
Yup, yup, yup.

06:48.375 --> 06:49.841
Got a lot stronger.

06:52.079 --> 06:53.578
Where'd you get the gum?

06:54.882 --> 06:56.148
Great, thank you.
-Okay.

06:59.086 --> 07:00.552
Out of the way, Leonard.

07:00.553 --> 07:02.019
Leonard:
<i> What's that book</i>
<i> that you're reading?</i>

07:02.356 --> 07:05.357
Here, and then you pull...

07:05.359 --> 07:09.161
There's this one part where
T-Rex puts this other-

07:10.330 --> 07:11.630
Here it is.

07:13.133 --> 07:14.299
Leonard:
<i> I love storybooks.</i>

07:14.301 --> 07:16.368
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

07:22.943 --> 07:25.010
All this open wilderness
and you're still underfoot.

07:25.946 --> 07:27.212
I wanna help.

07:27.981 --> 07:29.881
Well then stay out
of the bloody way.

07:31.952 --> 07:33.652
I'm not here to babysit, Will.

07:35.155 --> 07:37.923
Vernon:
<i> Ooh, (laughs) you</i>
<i> got told off.</i>

07:37.925 --> 07:41.793
(upbeat jazz music)

07:41.795 --> 07:43.295
Oh, good enough.

07:43.297 --> 07:49.134
(upbeat jazz music)

07:49.136 --> 07:54.206
(train bell rings)

08:08.889 --> 08:14.860
(gentle instrumental)

08:14.862 --> 08:17.929
¶

08:24.905 --> 08:31.276
¶

08:31.278 --> 08:32.410
Conductor:
<i> Peterboro'.</i>

08:32.412 --> 08:33.879
<i> Next stop, Peterboro'.</i>

08:37.618 --> 08:44.089
(soft instrumental)

08:44.091 --> 08:49.461
(humming)

08:49.463 --> 08:51.530
(soft instrumental)

08:51.532 --> 08:53.198
Sydney:
<i> George Waller, at last.</i>

08:53.200 --> 08:54.466
I got a later train.

08:54.735 --> 08:56.001
Here, take this, Ray.

08:56.537 --> 08:57.802
Good to see you, too.

08:59.373 --> 09:00.539
All right, boys,
it's rough water,

09:00.541 --> 09:02.207
so let's all work together.

09:02.209 --> 09:03.909
All right, let's go!

09:10.384 --> 09:12.050
Arthur:
<i> How many can't swim?</i>

09:12.252 --> 09:13.518
About half.

09:14.388 --> 09:16.288
And those who can
need improvement.

09:18.392 --> 09:19.958
And then there's Vernon.

09:19.960 --> 09:21.660
<i> He's a fish, that one.</i>

09:22.596 --> 09:24.262
<i> Couple lifeguard medals.</i>

09:25.499 --> 09:26.965
(whistle blows)

09:26.967 --> 09:28.533
Vernon:
<i> Last one there has to</i>
<i> bunk beside Frank.</i>

09:28.535 --> 09:30.368
You wanna swim now fellas?
Waller:<i> Sure.</i>

09:37.444 --> 09:39.277
Samuel de Champlain

09:39.279 --> 09:42.047
recorded his travels to
Balsam Lake in his diary.

09:42.049 --> 09:44.115
<i> The Ojibway had a</i>
<i> settlement here,</i>

09:44.885 --> 09:47.385
<i> used the lake as</i>
<i> their travel route.</i>

09:47.387 --> 09:49.287
<i> They hunted these very woods.</i>

09:49.856 --> 09:51.923
<i> They lived and they died here.</i>

09:52.626 --> 09:54.559
They're buried
beneath your feet.

09:54.561 --> 09:55.894
(sneezes)

09:55.896 --> 09:58.697
Robert:
<i> Centuries later,</i>
<i> voyageurs portaged here</i>

09:58.699 --> 10:00.665
<i> and stopped for the night.</i>

10:00.667 --> 10:02.734
Slept right under
their canoes.

10:04.504 --> 10:07.672
Now all you know each other,
but Mister Lambden's new,

10:07.674 --> 10:09.140
<i> so give him your respect.</i>

10:09.676 --> 10:12.410
I hope to meet all of you
individually throughout the day.

10:13.513 --> 10:16.514
At this camp, you'll get
out of it what you put in.

10:16.516 --> 10:18.516
Games, duty, devotion.

10:20.287 --> 10:21.853
Canon Rutherford is arriving
the day after tomorrow,

10:21.855 --> 10:24.756
so expect a series of
lectures on Wednesday.

10:25.692 --> 10:26.958
Questions?

10:28.762 --> 10:30.028
Mr. Wigington.

10:30.931 --> 10:32.631
When does Waller get here?
(boys chuckle)

10:34.735 --> 10:37.168
The rest of the boys are
paddling up from Peterborough

10:37.170 --> 10:38.670
with Mister Manley.

10:38.672 --> 10:39.671
Oh, that's great.

10:39.673 --> 10:41.172
Jack:
<i> We get to hear his stories.</i>

10:42.342 --> 10:43.908
Go ahead.

10:43.910 --> 10:46.645
(boys cheering)

10:47.914 --> 10:49.481
Don't have a
hypersensitivity to water,

10:49.483 --> 10:50.982
do you, Leonard?

10:51.585 --> 10:53.184
Mister Lambden.

10:53.186 --> 10:57.255
(screaming)

10:57.691 --> 10:59.190
His father drowned.

10:59.926 --> 11:01.526
Oh god, I'm an idiot.

11:01.528 --> 11:02.794
You didn't know.

11:04.464 --> 11:06.865
Leonard, go light the
stove, would you?

11:06.867 --> 11:08.133
Mhm.

11:12.806 --> 11:15.373
You and Vernon'll have him
swimming in a few days.

11:16.076 --> 11:17.809
You do know how to swim?

11:17.811 --> 11:19.878
My father made sure of that.

11:20.213 --> 11:22.280
Most of these boys
don't have fathers.

11:22.816 --> 11:24.282
They never came back.

11:25.018 --> 11:27.485
<i>They're adrift, Mister Lambden.</i>

11:27.487 --> 11:28.753
<i> They've been feminized</i>
<i> by their mothers</i>

11:28.755 --> 11:30.155
<i> and their female teachers.</i>

11:30.157 --> 11:32.357
This modern world
does not serve them.

11:32.359 --> 11:34.759
I think it's a pretty
exciting time to be a boy.

11:34.761 --> 11:37.228
They spend all their days
sitting in front of the radio.

11:37.230 --> 11:38.463
They need to get outdoors.

11:38.465 --> 11:39.698
Well, sure, but-

11:39.700 --> 11:41.433
Canon Rutherford has

11:41.435 --> 11:44.135
always extolled the virtues
of a strenuous life.

11:44.137 --> 11:47.706
I heard of a Father Rutherford
who was at the Somme.

11:47.708 --> 11:49.741
He braved the front lines.

11:49.743 --> 11:52.143
Disobeyed his superiors
to be there.

11:52.145 --> 11:54.646
He's now Secretary of
the Anglican Council.

11:55.982 --> 11:57.882
Arthur:
<i> I look forward to his lecture.</i>

12:05.292 --> 12:11.196
(dramatic instrumental)

12:11.198 --> 12:16.267
(muted boys shouting
and laughing)

12:19.606 --> 12:22.874
(muffled screaming)
(water bubbling)

12:22.876 --> 12:27.011
(tense instrumental)

12:27.013 --> 12:29.180
(water splashing)

12:29.182 --> 12:30.682
Stick together!

12:32.953 --> 12:35.754
(boys screaming)

12:41.294 --> 12:43.261
Everybody to the canoe!

12:44.498 --> 12:45.764
Arthur:
<i> Goddammit!</i>

12:47.701 --> 12:49.934
Waller, get the paddles.

12:53.507 --> 12:55.573
Waller, fetch the canoe!

12:57.911 --> 12:59.410
Waller:
<i> Here it is, Coach.</i>

13:00.413 --> 13:02.380
Arthur:
<i> We need the paddles!</i>

13:04.818 --> 13:06.317
Allen!

13:06.319 --> 13:07.585
Yes!

13:08.355 --> 13:09.454
Burkett!

13:09.456 --> 13:10.755
Here!

13:11.358 --> 13:13.024
Burgess?

13:13.026 --> 13:14.459
Here!

13:14.461 --> 13:15.460
Robert:
<i> Clarke?</i>

13:15.462 --> 13:16.995
Here!

13:16.997 --> 13:18.296
Robert:
<i> Edwards?</i>

13:19.299 --> 13:21.566
Waller:
<i> Joseph, Joseph?</i>

13:21.568 --> 13:22.967
Vernon:
<i> Joseph?</i>

13:22.969 --> 13:24.235
<i> Joseph?</i>

13:24.671 --> 13:26.304
Joseph Edwards?

13:26.306 --> 13:27.806
Waller:
<i> Joe? Do you see him?</i>

13:28.408 --> 13:29.674
Boy:
<i> Joseph?</i>

13:30.644 --> 13:31.910
<i> Joseph?</i>

13:40.086 --> 13:42.453
(sombre instrumental)

13:42.455 --> 13:44.622
Robert:
<i> Well boys, there's</i>
<i> another wave.</i>

13:44.624 --> 13:46.024
(panicked chatter)

13:46.026 --> 13:49.861
Robert:
<i> Hold on, boys, and</i>
<i> stay close to the boat!</i>

13:49.863 --> 13:51.629
(panicked chatter)
(tense instrumental)

13:51.631 --> 13:53.498
Boy:
<i> Help!</i>

13:53.500 --> 13:55.967
(panicked screaming)

13:55.969 --> 13:57.569
(dramatic music)

13:57.571 --> 14:03.741
(water moving)

14:03.743 --> 14:06.144
(screaming)

14:07.247 --> 14:08.479
Boy:
<i> Waller!</i>

14:08.481 --> 14:09.147
<i> Waller!</i>

14:09.149 --> 14:10.682
(boys cheering)

14:10.684 --> 14:12.450
Boy:<i> Waller, wait!</i>
<i> -Whoo!</i>

14:12.452 --> 14:14.285
Arthur:
<i> So this is the war canoe?</i>

14:14.287 --> 14:15.453
Thirty-footer.

14:15.455 --> 14:17.155
Beautiful.

14:17.157 --> 14:19.757
Robert:
<i> Tomorrow we'll take her</i>
<i> across the lake to Coboconk.</i>

14:19.759 --> 14:21.860
<i> Fetch some supplies, canoes.</i>

14:22.662 --> 14:23.661
<i> We need 11.</i>

14:23.663 --> 14:25.029
Arthur:
<i> That many?</i>

14:25.031 --> 14:26.798
Robert:
<i> We need extra boys to</i>
<i> bring the canoes back.</i>

14:26.800 --> 14:27.799
Of course.

14:27.801 --> 14:29.367
We'll sleep on the beach,

14:29.369 --> 14:31.369
paddle back in the morning.

14:31.371 --> 14:32.804
Sounds like fun.

14:32.806 --> 14:34.806
There's a tuck shop
there, Gordon.

14:34.808 --> 14:36.708
If I can convince
my lieutenant here,

14:36.710 --> 14:38.409
we'll have shaved cherry ice.

14:38.411 --> 14:39.711
Yes, please.

14:42.816 --> 14:44.148
Robert:
<i> Welcome, voyageurs!</i>

14:44.150 --> 14:45.183
Greetings.

14:45.185 --> 14:47.051
<i> Our treasurer, Sydney Manley.</i>

14:47.053 --> 14:48.820
Arthur:
<i> Arthur Lambden.</i>

14:48.822 --> 14:49.921
Let me take that.

14:49.923 --> 14:51.222
Ah, thanks.

14:51.758 --> 14:54.759
And this hellion
is George Waller.

14:54.761 --> 14:56.060
Yeah.

14:58.064 --> 14:59.264
<i> Fall in, boys.</i>

14:59.266 --> 15:01.699
He has a fascination
with the war.

15:01.701 --> 15:03.601
Quite lucky he missed it.

15:05.105 --> 15:06.537
This is Ray Allen.

15:06.539 --> 15:07.872
He's a Sunday school teacher

15:07.874 --> 15:09.540
and plans on entering
the ministry one day.

15:09.542 --> 15:11.075
Oh, I'm not too sure
about that, Mr. Butcher.

15:11.077 --> 15:13.411
Well, time for
some fun, I say.

15:13.413 --> 15:14.679
Thank you.

15:16.216 --> 15:17.482
That any good?

15:18.051 --> 15:19.517
It's a swell story.

15:19.920 --> 15:21.986
Well, it's no Shakespeare.

15:22.489 --> 15:24.389
Fitzgerald's the
Lost Generation,

15:24.391 --> 15:25.657
like us.

15:25.659 --> 15:27.258
Is that what we're called?

15:27.260 --> 15:28.293
Waller:
<i> Hey, Gordon!</i>

15:28.295 --> 15:29.327
Gordon:
<i> What?</i>

15:29.329 --> 15:30.328
George Waller!

15:30.330 --> 15:31.529
Leave him alone!

15:31.531 --> 15:32.664
I'm not doing anything.

15:32.666 --> 15:34.166
Uh oh, George.

15:34.167 --> 15:35.667
Robert:
<i> Unpack your gear or</i>
<i> rake the latrine.</i>

15:35.669 --> 15:36.701
Jack:
<i> How was it?</i>

15:36.703 --> 15:37.702
Waller:
<i> Aces.</i>

15:37.704 --> 15:39.270
You shoulda met us
in Peterborough.

15:39.272 --> 15:40.672
My mom made me come on a bus

15:40.674 --> 15:42.340
with my little brother.

15:42.342 --> 15:44.108
Hey, Willy Killjoy.

15:44.110 --> 15:45.643
I haven't seen you
since last summer.

15:45.645 --> 15:46.711
I'm Will now.

15:46.713 --> 15:48.379
Oh, you've grown.

15:48.381 --> 15:49.614
Will:
<i> Two inches.</i>

15:49.616 --> 15:51.282
Yeah, you've grown funny.

15:51.551 --> 15:52.884
(laughs)

15:52.886 --> 15:55.053
Waller:
<i> Now, Jack, tell</i>
<i> me all about her.</i>

15:55.055 --> 15:56.788
<i> Don't skimp on any of</i>
<i> the dirty details.</i>

15:56.790 --> 15:57.855
(whistle blows)

15:57.857 --> 15:59.457
(shouting and chattering)

15:59.459 --> 16:00.458
I'm open!

16:00.460 --> 16:02.060
Pass it!

16:02.062 --> 16:04.662
(shouting and chattering)

16:04.664 --> 16:05.997
Right here!

16:05.998 --> 16:07.331
Boy:
<i> We're on the same</i>
<i> team, Waller!</i>

16:07.334 --> 16:08.399
Jack:
<i> Right here! Come on!</i>

16:08.401 --> 16:09.367
- Leonard, incoming!

16:09.369 --> 16:10.735
Arthur:
<i> Work as a team!</i>

16:10.737 --> 16:12.337
Vernon:
<i> Come on, pass it!</i>

16:12.339 --> 16:13.871
Boys:
<i> Oh, whoa.</i>

16:13.873 --> 16:15.940
(laughing)
(whistle blows)

16:17.377 --> 16:18.409
Jack:
<i> Look out.</i>

16:18.411 --> 16:19.410
<i> Waller's here.</i>

16:19.412 --> 16:20.411
Sorry-
Waller:<i> You little prick.</i>

16:20.413 --> 16:21.412
Vernon:
<i> Whoa, hey, hey, hey.</i>

16:21.414 --> 16:22.413
Stop, stop, stop.
(whistle blows)

16:22.415 --> 16:23.414
Waller:
<i> That wasn't fair!</i>

16:23.416 --> 16:24.682
Enough!

16:25.018 --> 16:26.517
Boys:
<i> Oooh.</i>

16:26.519 --> 16:28.186
Arthur:
<i> All right, okay.</i>

16:29.456 --> 16:30.755
(Waller cries out)

16:31.057 --> 16:32.423
Take a walk.

16:32.425 --> 16:33.925
Calm down.

16:47.340 --> 16:48.940
Mr. Lambden,

16:48.942 --> 16:50.641
<i> you're in charge now.</i>

16:54.981 --> 16:56.247
(whistle blows)

16:57.650 --> 17:00.551
Arthur:
<i> Okay, boys, back to it.</i>

17:02.055 --> 17:03.755
What's the axe for?

17:08.094 --> 17:10.294
Don't be sore because
I play to win.

17:10.296 --> 17:13.865
Robert:
<i> You aren't even aware</i>
<i> that there's other players.</i>

17:13.867 --> 17:15.333
It's the George Waller game.

17:15.335 --> 17:16.801
I'm a good player.

17:16.803 --> 17:19.237
And you think that's how
a captain leads his team?

17:19.239 --> 17:21.205
If my captain was like you,

17:21.207 --> 17:22.306
I would be dead.

17:22.308 --> 17:24.208
It's a screwy game.

17:24.210 --> 17:26.677
That has been played on this
lake for thousands of years.

17:26.679 --> 17:27.779
<i> Warriors specific-</i>

17:27.781 --> 17:29.147
Waller:
<i> Oh, fine, then,</i>
<i> I'm a warrior.</i>

17:29.149 --> 17:30.748
Robert:
<i> A warrior's goal</i>

17:30.750 --> 17:33.718
<i> is to bring honour and</i>
<i> glory to their tribe.</i>

17:33.720 --> 17:35.219
Not themselves.

17:42.562 --> 17:44.262
Last camp left firewood.

17:45.131 --> 17:47.799
Pick on something
bigger than yourself.

17:47.801 --> 17:49.600
It's a tree.

17:49.602 --> 17:51.502
I never cut down a
tree in my life.

17:56.409 --> 17:57.875
That's your problem.

17:59.079 --> 18:00.978
Waller:
<i> Well you can't make me.</i>

18:03.650 --> 18:07.718
(breathing heavily)

18:16.796 --> 18:18.296
(Waller cries out)

18:20.366 --> 18:22.433
(grunting)

18:26.339 --> 18:32.276
(gentle instrumental)

18:32.278 --> 18:35.346
¶

19:17.390 --> 19:21.459
(wood snapping)

19:36.543 --> 19:37.542
Whoa.
-Crap.

19:37.544 --> 19:38.843
Oh my god.
-Oh my god.

19:38.845 --> 19:39.844
Waller, you do this?

19:39.846 --> 19:41.145
Waller:
<i> Whoohoohoo!</i>

19:41.146 --> 19:42.445
Vernon:
<i> That wasn't you.</i>
<i> This is you?</i>

19:42.448 --> 19:44.615
(overlapping
disbelieving praise)

19:44.617 --> 19:46.017
This is him?

19:46.019 --> 19:47.285
<i> What? (chuckles)</i>

19:56.930 --> 19:59.063
Amazing.

19:59.065 --> 20:00.064
Come here!

20:00.066 --> 20:01.899
Whoo, yeah!

20:01.901 --> 20:03.167
Oh!

20:04.270 --> 20:05.736
(boys laugh)

20:05.738 --> 20:11.075
(gentle music)

20:11.077 --> 20:16.581
¶

20:16.583 --> 20:17.815
(water splashing)

20:17.817 --> 20:19.083
Will:
<i> Jack!</i>

20:21.487 --> 20:23.487
Get the youngest up!

20:26.359 --> 20:28.426
Be careful you
don't bust a hole.

20:31.130 --> 20:32.663
You're bleeding.

20:32.665 --> 20:33.931
What?

20:37.303 --> 20:38.569
Robert?

20:39.038 --> 20:40.304
Robert?

20:49.882 --> 20:53.251
(gasps)

20:53.253 --> 20:54.318
You can't swim
with your knees.

20:54.320 --> 20:55.553
Get up.
-No!

20:55.555 --> 20:56.821
Now!

20:59.726 --> 21:00.858
Boys in the water,

21:00.860 --> 21:02.994
take off your shoes,
anything heavy.

21:04.931 --> 21:07.832
<i> Take off your trousers,</i>
<i> they'll drag you down!</i>

21:18.144 --> 21:19.944
Where did we capsize?

21:19.946 --> 21:22.446
Gordon, where did we capsize?

21:22.448 --> 21:24.348
Gordon:
<i> Near Grand Island, I think.</i>

21:25.318 --> 21:27.385
Robert:
<i> What are the chances</i>
<i> of us gaining a shore?</i>

21:28.955 --> 21:30.955
Do you see the shore?

21:35.728 --> 21:36.961
Oliver:
<i> Mr. Butcher?</i>

21:36.963 --> 21:38.362
Mark's hurt.

21:38.364 --> 21:39.797
He banged his head.

21:39.799 --> 21:41.499
I'm fine, I'm fine!

21:42.869 --> 21:44.368
I'll go.

21:50.043 --> 21:52.109
We need to stop the bleeding.

21:52.111 --> 21:53.377
Oliver:
<i> Here.</i>

21:54.981 --> 21:56.447
Arthur:
<i> Wrap it up.</i>

21:57.684 --> 21:59.750
Mark, switch spots with me.

22:00.353 --> 22:01.752
Stay where you are.

22:01.754 --> 22:02.920
There's room.

22:02.922 --> 22:04.355
It's not about room!

22:04.357 --> 22:05.807
We'll lose buoyancy.

22:05.808 --> 22:07.258
<i> If we try and flip it it will</i>
<i> fill up with water and sink.</i>

22:07.260 --> 22:08.759
I'm coming down.

22:09.729 --> 22:12.797
I can't dive for you
every time you sink.

22:22.542 --> 22:24.375
<i> ¶ My paddle's</i>
<i> keen and bright</i>

22:24.377 --> 22:25.643
<i> ¶ Flashing with silver</i>

22:25.645 --> 22:27.611
<i> ¶ Follow the wild</i>
<i> goose flight</i>

22:27.613 --> 22:29.847
<i> ¶ Dip, dip and swing ¶</i>

22:29.849 --> 22:31.615
¶ Dip, dip and
swing her back

22:31.617 --> 22:33.884
¶ Flashing with silver

22:33.886 --> 22:35.519
¶ Follow the wild
goose flight

22:35.521 --> 22:37.722
¶ Dip, dip and swing ¶

22:37.724 --> 22:40.391
¶ Get up, get out of bed

22:40.393 --> 22:43.361
¶ Cheer up, cheer up,
the sun is red

22:43.363 --> 22:44.829
¶ Live, live

22:44.831 --> 22:45.930
¶ Love, love

22:45.932 --> 22:48.065
¶ Laugh and be happy ¶

22:48.067 --> 22:53.738
(gentle instrumental)

22:53.740 --> 22:55.005
Oh, wow.

22:55.942 --> 22:57.241
Ohh.

22:58.578 --> 23:01.078
(applauding)

23:01.080 --> 23:02.513
(gentle piano music)

23:02.515 --> 23:12.523
(off beat notes)

23:15.628 --> 23:16.694
(squeaking)

23:16.696 --> 23:18.162
(laughing)

23:19.065 --> 23:25.436
(lively harmonica music)

23:25.438 --> 23:28.105
Waller:
<i> Then will he strip his</i>
<i> sleeve and show his scars,</i>

23:28.107 --> 23:31.675
<i> and say "These wounds</i>
<i> I had on Crispin's day."</i>

23:31.677 --> 23:35.813
<i> Old men forget; yet</i>
<i> all shall be forgot,</i>

23:35.815 --> 23:38.349
But he'll remember,
with advantages,

23:38.351 --> 23:40.251
What feats he did that day.

23:40.753 --> 23:42.953
From this day to the
ending of the world,

23:42.955 --> 23:45.089
but we in it shall
be remembered,

23:45.091 --> 23:49.827
We few, we happy few,
we band of brothers;

23:49.829 --> 23:53.030
<i> For he to-day that</i>
<i> shed his blood with me</i>

23:53.032 --> 23:54.532
<i> Shall be my brother.</i>

23:55.368 --> 23:56.634
(in unison) Amen.

23:59.739 --> 24:02.373
We need 11 boys to take
the canoe across the lake.

24:02.375 --> 24:05.643
Sign up with Mr. Lambden
throughout the day tomorrow.

24:05.645 --> 24:07.445
<i> Vernon, Waller?</i>

24:07.447 --> 24:08.546
<i> We'll need you in</i>
<i> the engine room.</i>

24:08.548 --> 24:10.381
I'm sore from the trip up.

24:11.150 --> 24:12.650
Sometimes God uses
pain as a chisel

24:12.652 --> 24:14.351
to model human character.

24:14.353 --> 24:16.754
Tell God to take
it easy already.

24:16.756 --> 24:17.922
(stifled laughter)

24:17.924 --> 24:19.523
Excuse me?

24:19.525 --> 24:20.925
I'm coming.

24:20.927 --> 24:22.092
I'll go.

24:22.094 --> 24:23.794
I wanna mail a letter.

24:24.230 --> 24:25.496
Leonard?

24:26.232 --> 24:27.898
Will?

24:27.900 --> 24:29.400
You'll be sure to volunteer?

24:29.402 --> 24:30.668
(sighs)

24:38.244 --> 24:43.314
(loon calling)
(wolf howling)

24:57.597 --> 24:58.863
Ray?

25:00.466 --> 25:01.999
<i> Raymond?</i>

25:02.001 --> 25:03.267
What?

25:04.837 --> 25:06.103
I was wondering.

25:07.373 --> 25:09.273
Since you're joining
the priesthood,

25:10.009 --> 25:11.909
does that mean you're
not allowed to-

25:12.812 --> 25:13.878
beat the bishop?

25:13.880 --> 25:16.947
(laughter)

25:19.519 --> 25:21.485
Dileas Gu Brath.

25:21.487 --> 25:23.454
Digitus Impudicus.

25:27.059 --> 25:28.559
Where are you going?

25:29.195 --> 25:30.294
None of your potatoes.

25:30.296 --> 25:32.696
The adults need
a smoke, Willy.

25:32.698 --> 25:34.665
I'm just going outside

25:34.667 --> 25:36.734
and I may be some time.

25:39.205 --> 25:40.838
Will:
<i> What's that from?</i>

25:40.840 --> 25:42.106
Ray:
<i> Laurence Oates?</i>

25:42.742 --> 25:44.408
Have you ever heard
the story of

25:44.410 --> 25:46.744
Captain Scott's
expedition to the South Pole?

25:46.746 --> 25:48.212
Yeah, they get lost
in a blizzard.

25:48.214 --> 25:49.380
Everyone was
starving and dying.

25:49.382 --> 25:50.648
Ray:
<i> That's right.</i>

25:51.284 --> 25:55.252
Laurence Oates was
the worst of the lot.

25:55.254 --> 25:58.789
His feet were
frostbitten, gangrenous.

25:58.791 --> 26:00.891
He was slowing
down the group,

26:00.893 --> 26:03.027
and he knew

26:03.029 --> 26:05.429
that if Captain Scott and the
others wanted to make it out,

26:05.431 --> 26:08.032
they'd have to
leave him behind.

26:08.034 --> 26:11.435
So one night,

26:11.437 --> 26:13.404
he walks out
of the tent,

26:13.406 --> 26:16.073
right into a snowstorm,
it's minus 40,

26:16.075 --> 26:17.975
and the last thing
that he said was-

26:17.977 --> 26:19.610
(fart)

26:19.612 --> 26:21.412
(laughing)

26:21.414 --> 26:23.247
Oh my goodness.

26:24.016 --> 26:26.517
Please excuse me,
do continue, Raymond.

26:26.919 --> 26:28.185
Will:
<i> That reeks.</i>

26:28.654 --> 26:30.354
You're an asshole.

26:32.191 --> 26:34.925
(chuckling)

26:44.470 --> 26:54.378
(humming)

27:15.868 --> 27:17.935
(sighs)

27:35.921 --> 27:37.821
Where did you serve?

27:40.493 --> 27:41.792
Ypres.

27:44.230 --> 27:45.496
Massacre.

27:47.600 --> 27:49.033
You?

27:49.035 --> 27:50.467
Somme.

27:50.469 --> 27:52.703
The infantry.

27:52.704 --> 27:54.938
I fell in a shell hole
and buggered up my knee.

27:54.940 --> 27:59.143
Some pals dragged me
out before I drowned.

27:59.145 --> 28:00.611
You were lucky.

28:01.714 --> 28:04.782
Four men pulled me out,
one brought me back.

28:05.284 --> 28:06.583
Not lucky.

28:07.186 --> 28:11.488
I became an orderly
with General Currie.

28:11.490 --> 28:13.957
Carried the Allied
colours into Mons.

28:15.895 --> 28:17.528
What was Currie like?

28:18.364 --> 28:21.999
He was respected,
Mr. Lambden,

28:22.001 --> 28:24.068
but he didn't win
the men over.

28:24.837 --> 28:27.071
Could you call me Arthur?

28:27.073 --> 28:29.073
I reckon a boys' camp
is the last place

28:29.075 --> 28:30.974
to stand on ceremony.

28:32.878 --> 28:34.778
Robert.

28:34.780 --> 28:36.947
Mr. Butcher in
front of the boys.

28:36.949 --> 28:38.248
Of course.

28:43.089 --> 28:45.222
He doesn't let me
smoke in here.

28:45.224 --> 28:46.490
<i> (chuckles)</i>

28:48.594 --> 28:51.095
Sydney:
<i> What time are you</i>
<i> setting that for?</i>

28:51.097 --> 28:52.362
4:30.

28:54.066 --> 28:56.433
You know, I grew
up on a farm

28:56.435 --> 28:59.403
and my dad woke me at five.

28:59.405 --> 29:00.404
Those were the days.

29:00.406 --> 29:02.673
A father taught
his son a trade.

29:02.675 --> 29:04.575
Sydney:
<i> I hated growing up on a farm.</i>

29:06.378 --> 29:08.545
We were just telling
old war stories.

29:10.916 --> 29:12.583
He served at Ypres.

29:15.121 --> 29:18.422
<i> 100,000 boys in one day.</i>

29:18.424 --> 29:21.325
(gentle guitar strumming)

29:21.327 --> 29:23.160
In my interview,

29:23.162 --> 29:26.230
they told me you were decorated
four times for bravery.

29:27.666 --> 29:30.067
Three, they were
being grandiose.

29:32.905 --> 29:34.404
Sydney:
<i> He's a humble hero.</i>

29:36.976 --> 29:39.643
A hero's just a man who's
too afraid to run away.

29:41.981 --> 29:45.048
(gentle guitar strumming)

29:47.219 --> 29:49.219
Thank god it
stopped raining.

29:49.221 --> 29:50.921
What time is it, Mark?

29:53.359 --> 29:55.425
My watch stopped
when it got wet.

29:56.595 --> 29:58.095
(coughing)

30:04.303 --> 30:06.703
(straining)

30:10.376 --> 30:11.642
Stop.

30:11.877 --> 30:13.343
Maybe we need more boys.

30:14.446 --> 30:16.213
There's nothing to
push us against her.

30:16.215 --> 30:17.548
What?

30:17.549 --> 30:18.882
There's nothing to push on,
no leverage, dummy.

30:18.884 --> 30:20.784
Waller:
<i> What'd you call me?</i>

30:20.786 --> 30:21.885
I knew this wouldn't work.

30:21.887 --> 30:23.053
It's not a kayak.

30:23.055 --> 30:25.088
Why don't you shut
your pie hole, Vern?

30:25.090 --> 30:26.356
Arthur:
<i> Boys.</i>

30:36.135 --> 30:38.268
<i> You boys get back</i>
<i> on the boat.</i>

30:38.270 --> 30:41.505
<i> Mr. Butcher, we can't</i>
<i> break the water seal.</i>

30:42.508 --> 30:44.608
We don't have paddles, anyway.

30:44.610 --> 30:46.510
Gee, Vernon, always
with the obvious.

30:47.479 --> 30:49.847
Can't the boys back
at camp do something?

30:49.849 --> 30:51.949
Vernon:
<i> They probably think</i>
<i> we're safe on land.</i>

30:53.953 --> 30:55.219
Come on.

30:57.323 --> 30:59.223
If we overload (mumbles).

31:04.296 --> 31:06.630
How long can these
boys stay immersed?

31:08.067 --> 31:09.366
Another hour.

31:12.004 --> 31:14.638
The water gets colder
the deeper the body is.

31:17.276 --> 31:18.375
The higher the body,

31:18.377 --> 31:20.010
the less heat you'll lose!

31:20.012 --> 31:21.078
<i> Come on, boys,</i>

31:21.080 --> 31:22.579
<i> keep yourselves up!</i>

31:24.116 --> 31:25.515
We'll take shifts,

31:25.517 --> 31:26.984
on and off the hull.

31:29.021 --> 31:30.921
It's not the water
I'm concerned about.

31:31.223 --> 31:34.124
(mumbling) Joseph had a
piano recital coming up.

31:44.837 --> 31:47.537
We need to make our
way to Grand Island.

31:49.842 --> 31:51.041
It's that way.

31:55.915 --> 31:57.180
Mr. Lambden,

31:58.617 --> 32:00.517
please, we have to try.

32:04.056 --> 32:05.689
Everybody stern.

32:05.691 --> 32:06.757
What?

32:06.759 --> 32:08.258
Robert:
<i> You heard Mr. Lambden.</i>

32:10.496 --> 32:11.995
We can do this.

32:16.335 --> 32:17.334
<i> Leonard?</i>

32:21.140 --> 32:22.606
This is a bad idea.

